I love tower defense style games. I got bored of this game quickly however after a couple levels however. Maybe I didn't play it long enough and unlock enough content but after playing 100 waves where the only variation was how many enemies appear, I just didn't care to play anymore. The towers are boring, the animations are boring but the graphics are clean and crisp. It just wasn't satisfying like how Tower Defense: Lost Earth is when you have a lot of waves.   Oh yeah, a lot of people complain about not being able to place towers on the edges of the map. What I did to get around this was pause the game, zoom in on the screen, then you can get to the edge and place your towers. This is highly annoying though.  It also did some weird glitch where I would end the game but the vibration track from the music seemed like it kept going after closing out the app. It was strange because I could barely feel the vibration after closing the app because it was so faint. It drained my battery very fast though for a few days before I figured out that it was the culprit. I had to restart my Galaxy S3 to make sure it was fully closed after killing the process and that was annoying as well.

A very enjoyable Tower Defense game. Unlike many others, we have the freedom to select the PATH the "attackers" take. This gives a lot of flexibility to the game - the challenge in the later levels is when the enemies get to take more than 1 entry/exit from the level. It's becomes difficult to plot something out in those cases.  My disappointment is with the lack of content. I really wish there were more maps and an increased variety of turrets. They have 4 unlocked in the beginning, with 2 more unlocking for the later "extended" maps, but by that point, since I've already completed the map, I'm no longer that enthusiastic to try them out.  There is an "endless" mode, but just the normal mode takes about 60 - 90 mins to complete. I'm too worn out to bother with that one.  It plays well on my Xperia Arc (custom ROM, android 4.x), loads fast enough and is smooth - no hitches or that stuff.

On this version (Galaxy S3) I cannot place a tower on the lowest possible row. When I touch a tower to place it, the graphic is offset to the upper-left, probably so that my finger doesn't hide the tower, but the problem is that when I try to place a tower on the lowest row, my finger is at the very edge of the screen yet the tower itself is placed on the second-to-last row. It then becomes physically impossible to place a tower on the very last row of a stage, which is absolutely crazy. As a level designer myself, this doesn't make the slightest sense and I'm wondering how the QA team didn't find this problem. The game is good and should earn a 5 star rating but a problem this ridiculous has me unable to play the game the way I want to and is therefore unacceptable in my opinion. Too bad I didn't not realize this before the 15 minute refund period ended. I am now stuck with a game that I can't play with unless they eventually fix this problem. Until then, 1 star is all it gets from me.

The game runs smoothly even on low-end devices. FieldRunners is based around the popular tower-defense mechanism, but with a twist: You decide the route the enemies take by blocking the way with your own units. It seems a bit late to the party, seeing as there are some very high-quality games available that implement the same type of gameplay, but FR brings a level of polish that other competitors just can't match. The menus, the backgrounds, the smooth animations: it all comes together beautifully.
